GraphClass.note:
	 A graph is gc_2 if its vertex set can be
	 partitioned into three possibly empty sets C, S and I, such that


C is a complete graph, I is independent and S (if non-empty)
	    induces a C_5;

every vertex in C is adjacent to every vertex in S;

every vertex in I is non-adjacent to every vertex in S.

Given a graph G, define G' as:

V(G') = {(x,y) | dG(x,y) = 2}

E(G') = {((x,y),(z,w)) | xzyw (in that order) is a P_4 in G or there is a vertex r in G such that xyrzw (in that order) is a \co{P_5} in G}

A graph G is gc_68 iff G' is bipartite.

A partial order < is a semi-order if any of the following equivalent coditions hold:
< is an interval order (x<y iff interval x lies entirely to the left of interval y) admitting an interval representation such that all the intervals are of unit length.
if x<y and z<w then either x<w or z<y (2+2 free) and if x<y and y<z then for all w either x<w or w<z (1+3 free)

	 A graph G=(V,E) is gc_950 if E can be partitioned into E1 and E2, and E2 can be transitively oriented by a relation F such that


(V,E1) is a gc_157 graph;

for all vertices x,y,z: if x->y \in F and yz \in E1 then xz \in E1.
